<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="420" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[685,1173,188,666]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,824,406,427]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named for its putative resemblance to bird (
<emphasis box="[906,944,432,454]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">avis</emphasis>
) feces (
<emphasis box="[1033,1093,432,454]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">faecus</emphasis>
), using Latin terms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="420" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[685,1173,188,666]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,822,486,507]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Discussion.</emphasis>
The flared elytral apices suggest a relationship with 
<taxonomicName authority="Waterhouse, 1889" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="squamulatus">
<emphasis box="[852,1048,512,534]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Agrilus squamulatus</emphasis>
Waterhouse, 1889
</taxonomicName>
and similar species, but the eye-like spots on the elytra are unusual and distinctive. See also the discussion for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hespenheide and Westcott" authorityYear="2018" box="[834,1000,592,614]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornithocoprus">
<emphasis box="[834,1000,592,614]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">A. ornithocoprus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Regrettably, the genitalia were destroyed by a dermestid subsequent to its imaging.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
